Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   External Affairs Minister Ill, Leaves for London </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    External Affairs Minister Ill, Leaves for London </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0806112894 Delhi INDIAN EXPRESS in English 6 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> BK0806112894 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi INDIAN EXPRESS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] New Delhi -- Union Minister for External Affairs 
Dinesh Singh will be out of action for the month as he is 
leaving or Monday for treatment in London. 
  Singh, who took over as External Affairs Minister a 
year-and-a-half ago, has kept indifferent health almost 
throughout the period. 
  Though Singh could not be contacted, his colleagues told 
INDIAN EXPRESS that the minister was leaving for London on 
Monday morning. He was likely to be away for a month, they said. 
  Through sheer coincidence, the top bureaucrat in the 
ministry 
is also not expected to be in Delhi for some days. Foreign 
Secretary K Srinivasan is also in a London Hospital; he flew 
there after catching malaria during his Bulgaria trip with 
President Shankar Dayal Sharma. 
  With an ailing cabinet minister at the top, much of the work 
is split among his two deputies, Ministers of State R L Bhatia 
and Salman Khurshid. 
  Bhatia has just returned from the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) 
Foreign Minister's Conference at Cairo, and Khurshid left on 
Sunday for a week-long trip to Kazakhstan, Kyrghizistan and 
Tajikstan. 
  With illness taking him to London, Dinesh Singh will be 
missing from the scene just when he might be needed at home. 
The Foreign Office should now be working at consolidating the 
gains of Rao's US visit, and another important summit is 
scheduled later this month when Rao flies to Moscow to meet 
President Boris Yeltsin. 
  Like always, Dinesh Singh's illness triggers off bouts of 
speculation about replacing him with a fitter man. The rumour 
mill has begun churning again; and Human Resource Development 
Minister Arjun Singh is now being mentioned as the man who might 
take over the ministry. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

