<DATE1>  8 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Manhunt' Launched To Rescue Hikers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Manhunt' Launched To Rescue Hikers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0806033794 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0245 
GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0806033794 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In Jammu Kashmir, militants kidnapped two British 
tourists, demanding the release of three foreign mercenaries 
belonging to the Harkatul Ansar outfit. The incident took place 
near Pahalgam yesterday. One of the kidnapped is the son of a 
journalist formerly based in Delhi. The security forces have 
launched a manhunt to secure their release. Militants also 
looted two foreigners of their belongings and cash at gunpoint 
at Aroo near Pahalgam. 
  In another incident, four persons, including two militants 
have been killed in the valley. The security forces nabbed 
eight militants and recovered a large quantity of arms and 
ammunition during search operations. Meanwhile, the indefinite 
curfew imposed in Bhaderwah and Kishtwar towns of Doda District 
is continuing. The curfew was imposed in Bhaderwah town 
yesterday morning following the killing of a BJP [Bharatiya 
Janata Party] leader by militants and the death of another 
person in violent incidents. In Kishtwar, the curfew was 
clamped as a precautionary measure. Security forces are 
patrolling vulnerable areas of both the towns. 

</TEXT>

