<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   Three Clauses of Barzani-Talabani Agreement Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Three Clauses of Barzani-Talabani Agreement Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0706135294 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 7 Jun 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> PM0706135294 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by 'Adnan Husayn: "Barzani and Talabani Agree To </F>
Halt Armed Conflict"] 
  [Excerpts] London -- The Iraqi Kurdish leaders Mas'ud 
Barzani and Jalal Talabani have agreed to end the fighting that 
continued between their militias during the past month and to 
eliminate the effects of the most extensive armed clashes Iraqi 
Kurdish areas have witnessed since they were placed under UN 
protection in the spring of 1991. 
  Barzani and Talabani held a meeting the day before yesterday 
in Irbil, capital of the Kurdish region. It is the first 
meeting since the armed confrontations broke out early in May. 
[passage omitted] The two Kurdish leaders' agreement includes 
three clauses: 
  -- A total cease-fire in all areas, including the areas 
adjacent to the border with Iran in al-Sulaymaniyah Governorate 
(where Patriotic Union of Kurdistan militias clashed with groups 
of Kurdish Islamists) 
  -- To form an operations room for the border areas, to 
consolidate the cease-fire there. This room should include 
representatives from Barzani's party, Talabani's party, the 
Unified Iraqi National Congress, the Kurdistan Front, and the 
Islamic Movement of Kurdistan. 
  -- To hold similar meetings later to solve outstanding 
problems, fully normalize conditions, and eliminate the effects 
of last month's events in various spheres. 
  Independent Kurdish sources believe that Barzani's and 
Talabani's meeting "was necessary to halt the Kurdish fighting." 
However, they warned of the eruption of "further clashes" in the 
future "if the two parties do not backtrack on their 
monopolization of power" in Iraqi Kurdistan "and reorganize 
conditions to form a (local) parliament and a government in 
which all parties are represented." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

