<H3> <TI>   PUK Sources Deny Sending Envoy to Baghdad </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PUK Sources Deny Sending Envoy to Baghdad </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0706155094 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 6 Jun 94 pp 1, 4 </F>
<F P=103> PM0706155094 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Zuhayr Qusaybati: "Talabani Meets With Barzani To </F>
Confirm Reconciliation and the Islamists Accuse Him of 
Negotiating With Baghdad"] 
  [Excerpts] London -- The Islamic Movement has renewed its 
campaign against the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan [PUK] led by 
Jalal Talabani, and it has accused the latter of sending a 
delegation to Baghdad to resume negotiations with the Iraqi 
Government. Talabani was due to meet yesterday with Kurdistan 
Democratic Party [KDP] Leader Mas'ud Barzani, his partner in the 
Kurdistan Front [KF] leadership, at the Shirin Palace Hotel in 
Shaqlawah for the first time since the fighting broke out 
between their two parties about a month ago. The fighting is 
believed to have left hundreds of casualties in northern Iraq. 
The purpose of the meeting is to confirm the reconciliation 
between the two parties. [passage omitted] 
  Meanwhile, PUK sources have denied that Talabani sent an 
envoy to Baghdad to negotiate with the Iraqi Government. The 
Islamic Movement in Kurdistan had claimed that the Kurdish 
leader had sent Shaykh 'Abd-al-Latif al-Barzanji to Baghdad on 
22 May and that the efforts of the latter, which coincided with 
the Kurdish infighting, made no progress. 
  The sources said "al-Barzanji is an Irbil merchant who has 
no links with the PUK." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

