<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   KDP, Islamic Movement Seize 2 Key Towns From PUK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    KDP, Islamic Movement Seize 2 Key Towns From PUK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706185194 Tehran IRNA in English 1800 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0706185194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sanandaj (Kurdistan Prov.), June 7, IRNA -- The 
north eastern Iraqi cities of Banjwin and Qal'at Dizah have been 
taken over by forces loyal to Iraq's Kurdistan Democratic Party 
(KDP) and the Islamic Movement Party (IMP) on Tuesday [7 June]. 
  According to an IMP spokesman scores of forces of Iraq's 
Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) were killed or injured in the 
clashes with the joint forces. 
  Latest dispatches from the area indicate that leaders of the 
warring groups are to start first round of their official talks 
in erbil on wednesday under supervision of the so-called iraqi 
national congress -- a loose grouping of various factions 
opposed to the regime in Baghdad -- to end the ongoing power 
struggle in Iraqi Kurdistan. 
  Irbil, the second major Kurdish city after Karkuk, has been 
declared capital of Iraqi Kurdistan by the self-proclaimed 
government of Kurds. The city is 15 kms away from the buffer 
zone which separates Kurdish controlled areas from the Iraqi 
forces. 

</TEXT>

