<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sweden Not To Contribute Money to Police Force </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sweden Not To Contribute Money to Police Force </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0706124094 Stockholm SVENSKA DAGBLADET in Swedish 6 Jun 94 
p 9 </F>

<F P=103> PM0706124094 </F>
<F P=104>  Stockholm SVENSKA DAGBLADET </F>
<F P=105>  Swedish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Bitte Hammargren: "Foreign Ministry `No' to </F>
Money for PLO"] 
  [Excerpt] The Swedish Foreign Ministry is saying a 
categorical "no" to contributing to the wage costs of the 
9,000-man Palestinian police force which has the difficult task 
of being responsible for security in Gaza and Jericho. Recently 
the new UN assistant secretary general, Norway's Terje Rod 
Larsen, called for international help to finance the police 
force. Without a functioning police force in Gaza there will be 
chaos, Terje Rod Larsen warned. 
  The PLO's coffers are more or less empty. The situation is 
so precarious that the Palestinian policemen in Gaza are not 
even having their wages paid to them. 
  The Foreign Ministry's message is the same which PLO leader 
Yasir 'Arafat heard from Prime Minister Carl Bildt during his 
visit to Stockholm in November last year. 
  However, Sweden is prepared to help with the training of the 
Palestinian police. 
  The Police High School in Solna has drafted a training 
program, said Alf Samulelson, Aid Minister Alf Svensson's under 
secretary of state. 
  The Swedish proposal, which has been passed on to the PLO, 
is 
about teaching forensic procedures and traffic surveillance. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

