<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Plan for Jordanian-Israeli Projects Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Plan for Jordanian-Israeli Projects Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0806144994 Paris Radio Monte Carlo in Arabic 1200 GMT 8 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0806144994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio Monte Carlo </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Randah Habib from Amman] </F>
  [Text] Next month Washington will launch a working plan to 
carry out economic projects between Jordan and Israel after 
these two countries have surmounted the most important obstacle 
to the progress of their bilateral negotiations, by forming a 
committee in Washington yesterday to demarcate joint borders. 
The committee will rotate meetings in Jordan and Israel 
starting in July. 
  The U.S. plan is based on two studies; the first is 
Jordanian 
and the other Israeli, which were presented in Washington. 
Washington will deduce the joint points included in the two 
studies to formulate a plan that is acceptable to both sides in 
order to be discussed by the tripartite committee in Washington 
next month. 
  The Jordanian file includes, in particular, the two seas 
canal plan, to link the Red Sea with the Dead Sea, while the 
Israeli plan speaks about linking the Mediterranean with the 
Dead Sea. 
  This Jordanian plan enjoys Washington's support, which 
considers it more realistic and useful, and closer to 
implementation. 
  Moreover, Amman no longer opposes the holding of the 
international economic conference on its territory. It will be 
held here next year, after a preparatory conference has been 
held in Morocco in November. 
  These developments come at a time when Prime Minister 
'Abd-al-Salam al-Majali is preparing to reshuffle his cabinet 
today in which he will introduce approximately 10 deputies. 
This will allow the participation of the legislative council in 
the decisions of the executive branch at a time when Jordan has 
expressed its readiness to sign a border agreement with Israel 
without waiting for the conclusion of a peace treaty. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-36382 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes111bb_94001" </HT>


