<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   Allied Use of Arab Facilities Protested </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Allied Use of Arab Facilities Protested </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Arab League Informed of `Violations' </H4>

<F P=102> JN0606115794 Baghdad INA in Arabic 1025 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> JN0606115794 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad INA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 6 Jun (INA) -- Iraq has protested to the Arab 
League General Secretariat against the continued facilities 
provided by the rulers of Saudi Arabia and Kuwait to U.S., 
British, and French aircraft violating Iraq's airspace, noting 
that this poses a serious threat to Iraq's security and 
sovereignty. 
  In a letter addressed to Arab League Secretary General Dr. 
'Ismat 'Abd-al-Majid, Iraq's permanent representative said these 
aircraft continued their violation of Iraqi airspace during the 
period 24-31 May. They carried out 352 sorties flying from 
their bases in Saudi Arabia and Kuwait. 
  Iraq's representative asked that the letter be circulated, 
along with a list detailing the violations, to the Arab member 
states to acquaint them with these regrettable facts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

