<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gur Denies Syrian Influence on Jordan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Gur Denies Syrian Influence on Jordan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0906085694 Tel Aviv IDF Radio in Hebrew 0500 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0906085694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv IDF Radio </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Deputy Defense Minister Mordekhay </F>
Gur by Ya'aqov Eylon and Mikhal Gazit; place not given -- live] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] [Eylon] Mr. Gur, is the 
attitude emanating from Amman inspired by Damascus? 
  [Gur] No. Unfortunately, Damascus is still unyielding. So 
far the Damascus attitude has been projected through the actions 
of Hizballah, rather than peaceful advances. That is why I 
attach such great significance to the Jordanian awakening. 
  [Gazit] Do you really believe Jordan awakened of its own 
accord, that it was not affected by the green light it has 
reportedly received from al-Asad? 
  [Gur] It is my opinion that it was an independent Jordanian 
decision. I do not know how far-reaching their decision is, but 
it is definitely not the result of Syrian prodding. I hope it 
will mature and progress. If it affects Syria in a positive 
direction, it will be doubly welcome. For myself, I see it as a 
new line adopted by Jordan, which does not want to be left out 
of the process -- which could happen, what with the continuing 
implementation of the arrangement between us and the 
Palestinians. 
  [Eylon] What they do want, Mr. Gur, is 320 square km between 
the port of al-'Aqabah and the Dead Sea. 
  [Gur] I am very well acquainted with the disputed issues. 
All these issues can be settled. I can tell you in no 
uncertain terms that there is no reason why Israel and Jordan 
should not reach an understanding quite quickly for the benefit 
of both sides. As far as Israel is concerned, such an 
understanding is important for the future of the negotiations 
with the Palestinians too, because it opens up new, important, 
and very consequential options for the next phases of 
negotiations. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

