<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin: Legislation on Jerusalem Considered </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rabin: Legislation on Jerusalem Considered </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0906064094 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 0405 GMT 9 Jun 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0906064094 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin by </F>
Me'ir Einstein on 9 June; place not given -- live or recorded] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] [Einstein] Mr. Prime Minister, 
we know the PLO has been trying to establish political facts in 
Jerusalem. What is the government doing about it? 
  [Rabin] We launched consultations on the Jerusalem situation 
two or three weeks ago, even before the public storm broke out. 
Organizations providing the Palestinian residents of the 
territories with services have been established over the years; 
some of them are fully justified. These include the Supreme 
Islamic Council, which is responsible for Temple Mount, a sacred 
site frequented by Palestinians from Judaea, Samaria, and Gaza. 
This council has been in charge of religious services since 
1967. There is the al-Maqasid Hospital, which has existed under 
different governments for many years, and which serves residents 
in and outside East Jerusalem. There are institutions in other 
fields devoid of any political significance. 
  We intend to explore the situation. As Israeli law applies 
to united Jerusalem, we may be forced to initiate special 
legislation to avert any PLO attempt to set up bodies of 
governing nature in Jerusalem. The PLO pledged that all 
Palestinian Authority bodies would be in Jericho during the 
interim period. We will insist on it even if special 
legislation is needed to ensure it. 
  [Einstein] What about Orient House activities? 
  [Rabin] If Mr. Faysal al-Husayni wants to be member of the 
Palestinian Authority, he will have to reside in Jericho. If he 
wishes to remain in Jerusalem, he will have to waive membership 
in the Palestinian Authority. 
  [Einstein] Does this mean we are going to close Orient 
House? 
  [Rabin] We will check the legal aspects. In fact, the 
attorney general has been doing it for about two weeks. A 
discussion on the issue was held in my office and a similar 
discussion was held at the Ministerial Committee on National 
Security Affairs. The discussions dealt with moves we should 
take to ensure that the agreement is adhered to and that all the 
governing authorities and their institutions be situated in 
Jericho, and not in Jerusalem during the interim period. 
  [Einstein] Thank you very much, Prime Minister Yitzhaq 
Rabin. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

