<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-'Attas on Recognition Prospects, Ties With North </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-'Attas on Recognition Prospects, Ties With North </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0906074394 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0618 GMT 9 Jun 93 </F>
<F P=103> NC0906074394 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 9 Jun (MENA) -- Engineer Haydar Abu-Bakr 
al-'Attas, who has been appointed prime minister in south Yemen, 
has warned that the persistence of the crisis will lead to major 
escalation and produce gloomy regional repercussions, including 
possible internationalization of the crisis. 
  In an interview with the newspaper AL-AHRAM published today, 
al-'Attas said: We are now limiting our efforts on reaching a 
cease-fire and agreeing on a formula for future conditions in 
the country. If Sanaa insists, however, on maintaining the 
crisis, the future will be bleak. 
  Al-'Attas praised Egypt's historic support for Yemeni 
interests since the 1970's up until the breakout of the recent 
ferocious civil war that Egypt, under the leadership of 
President Mubarak, is trying to stop. 
  Al-'Attas affirmed that if the northerners continue the war 
and escalate hostitilies, many countries may hasten to recognize 
the Democratic Republic of Yemen. 
  Al-'Attas accused Iraq of intervening to help Sanaa in the 
current fighting. 
  He said the war has undermined the union and made the 
division of Yemen a fact. He remarked that Yemen cannot be 
stable if it continues to comprise two warring states and for 
this reason a formula must be found that would preserve each 
state's independence while still maintaining some relationship 
between them. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

