<H3> <TI>   Aide Deplores `Terrorist' Israeli Actions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Aide Deplores `Terrorist' Israeli Actions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0706102894 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 7 Jun 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> PM0706102894 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Salwa al-Ustuwani: "Damascus Renews Its </F>
Rejection of `Majdal Shams First' Plan"] 
  [Excerpts] Damascus, Cairo, Amman, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT -- 
Damascus has informed Washington of its rejection of the Israeli 
peace plan conveyed by U.S. Secretary of State Warren 
Christopher during his recent shuttle tour of the region, known 
as the "Majdal Shams First" peace plan. 
  Well-informed sources in Cairo have told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT 
that the Israeli plan includes a three-phase Israeli withdrawal 
from the Golan Heights; the first phase includes a withdrawal 
from three out of five villages on the Heights. [passage 
omitted] 
  The sources pointed out that Israel does not want to 
implement an integrated peace process at once on all 
Arab-Israeli tracks. It is seeking to conduct partial and 
phased implementation on each track individually, with a 
transitional phase after the implementation of each peace plan. 
  Well-informed Syrian sources have told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT 
that 
Washington held meetings the evening of the day before yesterday 
with Syria, Lebanon, and Israel in preparation, the sources 
believe, for a discussion of the issue of Christopher's return 
to the region to continue his efforts regarding the peace 
process. [passage omitted] 
  In a statement to AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT a Syrian official held 
Israel responsible for increasing tension in the region and 
pushing the peace process toward collapse. 
  The official said that "Israel continues to deliberately 
escalate the situation and work to create a climate and 
conditions for continuing the war and exposing the Lebanese 
people's lives to danger and annihilation -- which threatens to 
destroy the peace process." The Syrian official stressed "the 
resoluteness of the Lebanese and Syrian position in the 
negotiation process, and no one can separate the two tracks." 
  The official added that "Israel's aggressive practices 
against Lebanon have exceeded all limits. No one can remain 
silent about them, they must be confronted. Israeli aggression 
must be confronted." The official urged the international 
community to put an end to the policy of murder and destruction 
which has become an integral part of Israel's strategy for the 
occupation of southern Lebanon. 
  The official described Israel's practices in southern 
Lebanon 
as terrorist actions, pointing out that this puts the region as 
a whole in a troubled and serious atmosphere and brings to mind 
the atmosphere of the war Israel is once again seeking. The 
official said: "Thus a prompt move is needed to stop Israeli 
practices, provocations, and the positions adopted by Yitzhaq 
Rabin's government," adding that Israel would be very mistaken 
if it believes that it can continue to have a free hand to 
strike as it wishes. It must realize well that Lebanese 
resistance is stronger than Israeli aggression, because it is a 
legitimate right and supported by international legitimacy." 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

