<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meeting Said To Lead to `Breakthrough' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meeting Said To Lead to `Breakthrough' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0906180494 Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network in 
Hebrew 1700 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0906180494 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin by </F>
correspondent Yaron Deqel on 9 June; place not given -- recorded] 
  [Text] Our political correspondent 'Imanu'el Rosen reports 
that high-level sources have confirmed that Prime Minister 
Yitzhaq Rabin held a secret meeting with King Husayn a few days 
ago. It was that meeting which led to the breakthrough in the 
talks between Israel and Jordan. Our correspondent Yaron Deqel 
today asked the prime minister about the secret contacts. 
Yitzhaq Rabin neither confirmed nor denied the meeting. 
  [Begin recording] [Deqel] Mr. Prime Minister, has progress 
with Jordan been achieved in the wake of some type of secret 
talks which were held recently? 
  [Rabin] I will not address myself to the reasons that led to 
this progress. I think there are many reasons, the main one 
being Jordan's willingness to make slow moves toward a peace 
treaty. Will this treaty be signed before progress is made with 
Syria, or not? I do not have an answer. [end recording] 
  [Later during the broadcast, political correspondent 
'Imanu'el Rosen relays a live report from Tel Aviv, stressing 
that "the recent breakthrough with Jordan was surely not 
accidental. A process of several weeks, of three weeks at 
least, involving secret contacts, away from the media, had taken 
place. The details of the recent meeting in Washington were 
concluded more than two weeks ago. Incidentally, even some of 
the delegation members were not aware of the nature of the 
agreement. In short, we were told by high-level sources that a 
meeting did take place between Yitzhaq Rabin and King Husayn. 
The prime minister's bureau refuses to confirm this meeting, 
but states that very high-level contacts indeed took place."] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

