<H3> <TI>   Finance Minister Discusses Rescheduling Foreign Debt </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Finance Minister Discusses Rescheduling Foreign Debt </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Hopes To Capitalize on Paris Club Deal </H4>

<F P=102> LD0406131894 Algiers Radio Algiers Network in Arabic 1200 
GMT 4 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0406131894 </F>
<F P=104>  Algiers Radio Algiers Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] The effective beginning of the period following 
the accord on rescheduling the public debt seems to be 
characterized by the government's control of available data and 
by drawing the main lines of the strategy in order to avoid as 
much as possible any negative repercussions -- all while 
eliminating any possible difficulty in the postagreement period. 
  All this transpires before highlighting the positive effect 
of the agreement, which often emerges in the long run. The 
statement by Finance Minister Ahmed Benbitour falls within this 
context. Benbitou stressed that the most important thing was the 
speed with which the loans obtained up to date from the IMF, in 
accordance with the agreement, will be used. Bachir Hedibel 
reports: 
  [Hedibel] During the period following the Paris Club 
agreement, which is the same period preceded by the transitional 
agreement with the IMF, the government will work to focus its 
efforts on reducing the budget deficit, so the latter will reach 
3.2 percent next year. This is the content of the statement 
made by the finance minister. 
  Benbitour hopes today for a speedy use of the loans granted 
to Algeria by the IMF or other financial institutions, or in 
accordance with the agreement with Paris Club. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

