<F P=100> ARAB AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Algeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Receives Malaysian Counterpart </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Receives Malaysian Counterpart </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0906132294 Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA in English 0856 GMT 9 Jun 
94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0906132294 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kuala Lumpur, June 9 (OANA-BERNAMA) -- Algeria has 
requested Malaysia's help to present its proposal for the 
establishment of ties between the Maghreb Union and ASEAN. 
  Algeria, this year's chairman of the Maghreb Union, made the 
request at a meeting between its foreign minister, Mohamed Salah 
Dembri and his Malaysian counterpart Abdullah Ahmad Badawi 
during the latter's four-day visit from June 5 to the country. 
  Senior officials of both countries were also present during 
the meeting. 
  A statement issued by the Malaysian Foreign Ministry 
Thursday 
[9 June], said Abdullah had promised to present Algeria's 
proposal at the annual meeting of ASEAN's foreign ministers in 
Bangkok next month. 
  He believed that there would be no objection to the proposal 
since ASEAN had established ties with several regional groupings 
such as the Gulf Cooperation Council, Rio Group and European 
Union. 
  Hopefully a meeting between ASEAN and the Maghreb Union 
could 
be held during this year's session of the United Nations (UN) 
General Assembly, the statement said. 
  During the visit, Abdullah also called on Algerian President 
General Lamine Zeroual, and held discussions with Prime Minister 
Mokdad Sifi. 
  During the bilateral discussions, both foreign ministers 
also 
felt that closer ties between Algeria and Malaysia could further 
strengthen the South-South cooperation particularly within the 
framework of Group-15. 
  Both countries also agreed on exchange of experience in 
economic development, training, technical cooperation, trade, 
investment, education and culture. 
  Being Islamic countries emphasising on development for the 
people, Malaysia and Algeria agree on exchange of ideas between 
their Islamic intellectuals on Islam and development, the 
statement said. 
  On enhancing economic cooperation, Malaysia and Algeria had 
agreed to look into and sign several agreements including those 
on economic, scientific and technical cooperation, investment 
protection and assurance, and waving of visa's requirement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

