<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Opposition Radio Causes `Measures' Against Egypt </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Opposition Radio Causes `Measures' Against Egypt </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0806191094 Cairo AL-'ARABI in Arabic 6 Jun 94 pp 1, 4 </F>
<F P=103> NC0806191094 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo AL-'ARABI </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Observers have not been able to find a reason for 
the escalation of the Sudanese measures against Egypt at this 
particular time. According to exclusive information available 
to AL-'ARABI, the reason is this: The Sudanese opposition radio 
station has begun its transmission and is now heard in Khartoum. 
The Sudanese Government holds Cairo responsible. 
  However, according to information, the opposition radio is 
being hired from an overseas country for $500 per hour, is 
transmitting to Sudan through satellite, and Cairo has 
absolutely nothing to do with it. In fact, Egypt had rejected 
numerous requests from the Sudanese opposition to allow the 
radio to transmit from Cairo, and this has worsened the 
relations between the two sides for several months. 
  The radio was launched by the personal efforts of some 
academic and military elements independent of the Sudanese 
opposition group. Those elements tried to activate the 
opposition in light of the poor performance of the National 
Sudanese Grouping as a result of disagreements between the Ummah 
Party and the Sudanese Communist Party over the grouping's 
internal structure. The disagreements also led to differences 
between the two main parties, the Ummah Party and the Democratic 
Unionist Party [DUP], and this necessitated the presence of DUP 
Chairman Muhammad 'Uthman al-Mirghani in Cairo to try to contain 
the crisis. 
  The danger of the opposition radio, which began two hours of 
transmission daily, is that it ends the isolation of the 
Sudanese citizen and obstructs the regime's media hegemony. 
This is a threat to the regime itself, especially given the 
worsening domestic problems. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-36563 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes112_k_94001" </HT>


