<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Says Kurdistan Situation `Under Control' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opposition Says Kurdistan Situation `Under Control' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0906151294 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 9 Jun 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> PM0906151294 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by 'Adnan Husayn: "Iraqi Opposition Stresses </F>
Situation in Kurdistan Under Control"] 
  [Excerpts] London -- An Iraqi opposition official has 
stressed that the situation in Iraqi Kurdistan is now under 
control after a month of armed conflict over power between the 
Kurdistan Democratic Party [KDP], led by Mas'ud Barzani, and the 
Patriotic Union of Kurdistan [PUK], led by Jalal Talabani. The 
conflict resulted in the deaths of at least 600 ordinary 
citizens from the two sides. 
  Dr. Ahmad al-Jalabi, head of the [Unified] Iraqi National 
Congress Executive Bureau, told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT over the 
telephone yesterday from his residence in the city of Salah 
al-Din in north Iraq that "life has returned to normal" in most 
Kurdish areas since the meeting held last Sunday between Barzani 
and Talabani. [passage omitted] 
  Asked about the clashes that broke out the day before 
yesterday in the Qal'at Dizah and Halabjah areas near the border 
with Iran, al-Jalabi said that the National Congress, which has 
been entrusted with the task of disengaging the warring 
militias, sent forces belonging to it to these areas yesterday 
"to disengage the forces and prevent fighting from breaking out 
between them." 
  PUK (Talabani) sources accused joint forces of the KDP 
(Barzani) and Kurdish Islamic organizations, which are accused 
of collaborating with Iran and the Iranian Revolutionary Guard, 
of attacking PUK positions in these areas. But sources from 
Barzani's party have denied that the KDP forces participated in 
these clashes, which they said took place between "PUK forces 
and Islamic Movement forces only." 
  AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT has learned that a tripartite meeting 
bringing together leaders from Barzani's party, Talabani's 
party, and the Islamic Movement was held yesterday in Irbil to 
discuss ways of stopping the clashes in the border areas. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

